    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
                <date>June 14.1849</date>
            </p>
            <p>Valued Friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I perceived in the last no of<lb/> the “Occident” an article written by<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Brown</persName> relative to the <date>Sunday</date><lb/> Laws of
                    <placeName>Pennsylvania</placeName>, and I regret<lb/> much that every effort
                has been in<lb/> vain to modify that obnoxious Law<lb/> in your state, a session
                before the<lb/> last of our Legislature when they revis-<lb/>ed our Criminal Laws I
                had the<lb/> matter under consideration in the<lb/> Senate nearly two days relative
                to<lb/> the <date>Sabbath</date> Laws here in which<lb/>
                <persName>Mr <sic>Stanard</sic></persName> and others took a very<lb/> active part.
                I think that I sent you<lb/> the papers containing the remarks<lb/> on the subject,
                they were however only<lb/> slightly modified and that only by<lb/> the casting vote
                of the speaker, the law<lb/> as reported by the revisers read thus<lb/> “If any
                person on <date>Sabbath</date> day shall<lb/> himself be found labouring &amp;c
                &amp;c” and<lb/> the amendment asked for in the Senate<lb/> was a proviso for
                persons who had<lb/> kept the <date>Sabbath</date> day of the congregation<lb/> to
                which they may have belonged to be<lb/> exempt from the penalty of the law</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>which was lost by a vote of 20 to 5<lb/> the amendment was then asked for to<lb/>
                insert the word “a” so as to read “If any<lb/> person on <hi rend="underline">a</hi>
                <date>sabbath</date> day “&amp;c &amp;c” and in order<lb/> to get that slight
                amendment it was<lb/> a tie vote the speaker giving the casting<lb/> vote. You will
                perceive that the<lb/> law as reported was done to recognize<lb/> a
                    <date>Sabbath</date> day and not to leave it dis-<lb/>cretionary with the
                magistrate to say<lb/> which was the <date>sabbath</date> day, the title<lb/> of the
                Chapter in which this law may<lb/> be found in Chap VIII “Of
                <sic>offences</sic><lb/> against Chastity Morality and Decency”<lb/> Revised Code
                    <date>1848</date> page III. <persName>Mr Mays</persName><lb/> and
                    <persName>Standard</persName> told me then that if<lb/> we had have had any
                    '<sic>competant</sic><lb/> person to have argued the point before<lb/> the
                committee we would have had<lb/> matters fixed our own way, but in<lb/> this
                particular we were minus.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We have now an extra session<lb/> of the Legislature for the purpose
                of<lb/> revising the Civil Code and I believe<lb/> the Criminal also. I regret that
                they<lb/> have adjourned from here to the<lb/> springs. I did intend to use my
                eff<lb/>orts to get this matter set right in</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>regard to that law, I <sic>seen</sic>
                <persName>Mr Standard</persName><lb/> to day and I had a long talk with<lb/> him on
                the subject and presented him<lb/> with a copy of the last 'Occident” he<lb/>
                assures me that he will use his efforts<lb/> to have it modified. I am sure
                were<lb/> you here and present at the legislature<lb/> you could urge our claims in
                such lan<lb/>guage before the committees that could<lb/> not be easily
                mis-understood, would to<lb/> God I had the ability I would do<lb/> my utmost to
                have things right, as they<lb/> ought to be I feel a great interest in<lb/> the
                matter and have enlisted many of<lb/>
                <sic>of</sic> the members of the Legislature from<lb/> time to time in our favour, I
                wish<lb/> you would write an article relative<lb/> to the matter, and if to the
                purpose<lb/> I am sure it will have the desired<lb/> effect I will have it published
                and<lb/> well distributed among the members,<lb/> you know that the petition you
                wrote<lb/> for me to the common Hall of this city<lb/> was the means of the repeal
                of the<lb/>
                <date>Sabbath</date> law of <placeName>Richmond</placeName>, and I am<lb/> sure with
                a little work we can accomplish<lb/> our end. Truly yours. <hi rend="underline"
                        ><persName role="author">Jacob Ezekiel</persName></hi></p>
            <p>Love to sister and all relatives</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>
                    <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>
                </placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>
                    <hi rend="underline">Pa</hi>
                </placeName>
            </p>
